  "text": "The complete chain from Deployment spec change to Pod creation in Kubernetes involves three controllers and the API server:\n\n## Deployment Controller Reconciliation\nWhen a Deployment spec changes, the Deployment Controller (pkg/controller/deployment/deployment_controller.go) detects the change through an informer and enqueues the Deployment. The controller's worker calls **syncDeployment** (line 590 in deployment_controller.go), which is the main reconciliation function. This function fetches the Deployment, retrieves all ReplicaSets owned by it, and then delegates to the appropriate strategy handler (rolling update, recreate, etc.) or calls **sync** (line 49 in sync.go) for status-only updates or scaling events.\n\n## ReplicaSet Creation\nThe **sync** function (sync.go:49) calls **getAllReplicaSetsAndSyncRevision** (line 116) which in turn calls **getNewReplicaSet** (line 138). This function either finds an existing ReplicaSet matching the Deployment's PodTemplateSpec or creates a new one. When creating a new ReplicaSet, it constructs a ReplicaSet object and calls **dc.client.AppsV1().ReplicaSets(d.Namespace).Create()** (line 224 in sync.go) to persist it through the Kubernetes API.\n\n## ReplicaSet Controller Reconciliation\nOnce the ReplicaSet is created, the ReplicaSet Controller (pkg/controller/replicaset/replica_set.go) is triggered through informers. Its worker calls **syncReplicaSet** (line 675), which is the main reconciliation function for ReplicaSets. This function retrieves the ReplicaSet, filters active pods, and then calls **manageReplicas** (line 569) to ensure the correct number of pod replicas exist.\n\n## Pod Creation\nThe **manageReplicas** function (replica_set.go:569) calculates the difference between desired and actual replicas. When more pods are needed, it uses a \"slow start\" approach and calls **rsc.podControl.CreatePods()** (line 598) for each batch. The podControl is a PodControlInterface implementation (RealPodControl defined in controller_utils.go:473) whose **CreatePods** method (line 530) delegates to **CreatePodsWithGenerateName** (line 534). This function constructs a Pod object using **GetPodFromTemplate** (line 553) and then calls **r.KubeClient.CoreV1().Pods(namespace).Create()** (line 582) to persist the Pod through the Kubernetes API.\n\n## API Server Pod Storage\nThe Pod creation request reaches the API server's Pod REST storage handler (pkg/registry/core/pod/storage/storage.go), where the **REST** struct (line 66) embeds a **genericregistry.Store**. The Store uses the Pod strategy (registrypod.Strategy) which handles creation validation and preparation, and ultimately persists the Pod object to the backing store (typically etcd). Similar storage handlers exist for ReplicaSets (pkg/registry/apps/replicaset/storage/storage.go) and Deployments (pkg/registry/apps/deployment/storage/storage.go).\n\nThis chain demonstrates how Kubernetes controllers manage desired state: Deployment Controller creates ReplicaSets, ReplicaSet Controller creates Pods, and each level is reconciled independently but hierarchically, with each resource type using the API server's REST storage for persistence."
}

